I've noticed that the `omitUnnecessaryFields` function pops up more and more often in our profiling traces, sometimes taking even 26% of the CPU time. It's clear that it does the complete opposite of what all JIT languages like - it alters the created structs. I replaced it with a `buildResult` function that creates an object dynamically, only with the properties that should be there.

This improvement made up roughly 70% of the results. But then I made the `arrayIndices` calculation lazy, and while it didn't change anything for Safari, it got me another significant improvement on V8.

<details>
<summary>Benchmarks</summary>

```ts
{
  const matcher = MinimongoTest.makeLookupFunction('a');
  const doc = { a: 1 };
  for (let round = 1; round <= 50; ++round) {
    console.time('simple');
    for (let _ = 0; _ < 10000; ++_) matcher(doc);
    console.timeEnd('simple');
  }
}

{
  const matcher = MinimongoTest.makeLookupFunction('a');
  const doc = { a: { b: { c: { d: { e: 1 } } } } };
  for (let round = 1; round <= 50; ++round) {
    console.time('complex');
    for (let _ = 0; _ < 10000; ++_) matcher(doc);
    console.timeEnd('complex');
  }
}

{
  const matcher = MinimongoTest.makeLookupFunction('a.b.c');
  const doc = { a: [{ b: [{ c: 1 }] }] };
  for (let round = 1; round <= 50; ++round) {
    console.time('arrays');
    for (let _ = 0; _ < 10000; ++_) matcher(doc);
    console.timeEnd('arrays');
  }
}
```

Aggregated using https://vazco.github.io/console-time-analyzer/.

